1. Introduction¶

Recall:¶

Suppose we have $X = (X_1, X_2, ..., X_p)$ is multivariate normal.
Then, the square of the Mahalanobis distance (MD) of the i$^{th}$ case or observation has the following property:

  • MD$^2_i$ = $(X - T(X))' C(X)^{-1} (X- T(X))$ ~ $\chi^2_p$

    where T(X) is an estimator of the population mean and C(X) is an estimator of the true covariance.

In the textbook$^{[1]}$, $T(X) = \bar{X}$ and $C(X) = S(X)$.
Then, we find a $i^{th}$ case or observation, given the level of significance $\alpha$, to be a outlier if MD$_i$ = $(x_i - \bar{x})' S(x)^{-1} (x_i - \bar{x})$ > $\chi^2_{p, 1-\alpha}$

However, the sample mean and sample covariance are vulnerable to even a single outlier when the sample size is relatively small



Therefore, we need robust estimators for the true mean and true covariance
Then, even if we have outliers, the estimates are not affected by them.

* In case of linear regression, outliers and leverage points could be found by using the standardized residuals and the diagonals of hat matrix.¶

* However, both the standardized residuals and the diagonals of the hat matrix are not also immune to outliers.¶

* Therefore, we also need robust estimators to find outliers and leverage points.¶

Note: The diagonal elements of a hat matrix are linearly related to the square of Mahalanobis distance

  • $h_{ii} = \frac{MD_i^2}{n-1} + \frac{1}{n}$

  • For the regression problem, the authors proposed to use a high-breakdown regression estimators,
    and as an example, the author briefly provided the least median estimator:
    • minimize$_{\theta}$ median$_{i = 1, 2, ... , n }$ $r^2_i (\hat{\theta})$

6. Conclusion:¶

  • First thing to make sure before using the method is whether the sample is approximately multivariate normal

  • When we had many outliers compared to the sample size, this robust measure detects outliers better than the classic method.

  • When the sample size is large and we have a small amount of outliers relative to the sample, you will see the similar results.
